{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637433"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17660"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17660"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.54,0.08,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17660"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61403"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10524"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24262"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe bladder must be able to accommodate increasing volumes of urine while maintaining relatively low pressures during the storage phase of micturition.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes bladder compliance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rate of urine production over time","Speed of detrusor muscle contraction","Change in bladder volume divided by change in detrusor pressure","Maximum volume before urge to void","Change in pressure divided by change in volume"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBladder compliance is defined as the \u003Cstrong\u003Echange in bladder volume divided by change in detrusor pressure\u003C/strong\u003E during bladder filling. This relationship describes how easily the bladder wall stretches to accommodate increasing volumes of urine while maintaining low storage pressures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erate of urine production over time\u003C/strong\u003E describes kidney function and urine output rather than the mechanical properties of the bladder wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espeed of detrusor muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E relates to the emptying phase of micturition rather than the storage phase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaximum volume before urge to void\u003C/strong\u003E describes bladder capacity rather than how well the bladder accommodates increasing volumes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Echange in pressure divided by change in volume\u003C/strong\u003E represents the inverse of compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal bladder compliance is essential for proper urinary storage. Poor compliance can result in high storage pressures that may damage the upper urinary tract through vesicoureteral reflux.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bladder compliance is defined as the change in volume divided by the change in pressure during bladder filling.","Normal bladder compliance allows for storage of increasing volumes of urine with minimal increase in pressure.","Low bladder compliance can lead to high storage pressures and risk of kidney damage."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, 